\begin_layout Subsection
Household discount factor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The household discount factor is permanently decreased by 1 percentage point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Households are more impatient (discount the future less) and increase their
 consumption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the short and medium term, this it works as a positive (but gradually
 declining) shock to private consumption and housing demand
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This sets in motion the following equilibrium responses:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Increased demand leads to increased production
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased sectoral production leads to increased sectoral production inputs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased material inputs leads to increased imports and domestic sectoral
 output
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased capital demand leads to increased investmens from imports and
 domestic sectoral output
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased labor demand leads to increased wages, employment and labor supply
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased employment and wages leads to higher household income and increased
 demand for private consumption and housing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased housing demand leads to increased housing prices and investments
 in housing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased housing prices lead to increased liquidity and demand for private
 consumption and housing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased production leads to higher output prices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Higher output prices lead to higher demand prices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased demand prices dampen demand over time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Full crowding out in employment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Positive short run effect on government budget
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The increased short and medium term consumption will reduce household wealth
 and long-run consumption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
55 years after the shock the negative effect on wealth has not stabilized.
 This is because of slow generational effects arising from our overlapping-gener
ations structure.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
We do see the negative effect on consumption, but this has also not stabilized
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Households live many years and give inheritance - so it will stabilize very
 slowly
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
In the long run it works as a negative shock to private consumption and
 housing demand
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There are negative long-run effect on the government budget and fiscal sustainab
ility
\end_layout

