\begin_layout Subsection
Wages through the Nash Negotiation Weight
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Nash negotiation weight is decreased permanently by 1 percentage point
 (workers bargaining power goes up).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Workers receive a larger share of the surplus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
On one hand, this increases household income and works as a positive demand
 shock to private consumption and housing - for an isolated analysis of
 this shock, refer to the demand shock via lump-sum transfers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
On the other hand, it tightens the wedge between the marginal product of
 labor and the wage
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This wedge needs to pay for hiring costs so firms reduce their labor demand
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For most other shocks, reduced labor demand lowers the wages, but here,
 the higher wages are the cause of the lower labor demand and structural
 unemployment increase
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The shock also works as a negative supply shock to labor - for an isolated
 analysis of this shock, refer to the supply shock to labor via participation
 (with the opposite sign)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Higher wages give higher unit costs and higher prices
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This lowers exports and increases import shares
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Real household income increases
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The effect from higher wages and lower employment makes the net-effect from
 wage income very small
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Larger unemployment is compensated and this increase household income this
 dominates effect from higher prices
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The shock is contractionary in employment
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
In the short run the employment gap is positive as actual employment rigidly
 decrease to its structural level
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
In the short run, the shock is expansionary in GVA and GDP, as a large permanent
 shift to more capital intensive production increases short term investments
 a lot and firms can increase utilization on labor and capital in the short
 run
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the medium and long term, the shock is also contractionary in GVA and
 GDP as labor input is permanently lower
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There is a negative long run effect on the government budget and fiscal
 sustainability
\end_layout

